sentences: Mary Joan Okum (née Kath; October 27, 1924 – December 8, 2015), known by her performing name Bonnie Lou, was an American musical pioneer, recognized as one of the first female rock and roll singers.
Bonnie Lou was one of the first female co-hosts of a successful syndicated  television talk show, and a regular musical performer on popular shows in the 1960s and 1970s.
She "was a prime mover in the first days of rockabilly," and is a member of the Rockabilly Hall of Fame.
Born in Towanda, Illinois, Kath's parents were Arthur (1899–1977) and Eva Kath (1905–2000).
